m Hungerford (Berkshire), from Old English <i>hungor</i> ‘hunger’, here probably denoting unproductive land, + <i>ford</i>. This surname has been established in Ireland since the 17th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Hungerford was born about 1060, in Normandy, France, his father, Walter De Hungerford I, was 15 and his mother, Mrs. Walter De Hungerford I, was 10. He had at least 1 son with De Hungerford. He died in 1100, in Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"about 1060–1100":"umbes 1060–1100","1060–1100":"1060–1100","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1045–Male":"1045–Surnud","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1080":"1080","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1100":"1100","1045":"1045","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Hungerford, Berkshire, England":"Hungerford, Berkshire, England","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1060–1100":"noin 1060–1100","1060–1100":"1060–1100","1060–Female":"1060–Kuollut","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1045–Male":"1045–Kuollut","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","1080":"1080","about 1060":"noin 1060","1100":"11